posts.name: Mike Schreiber
posts.cooked:
CacheCAD is a file management interface for Google Drive developed with Team 8096, Cache Money. Unlike the Google Drive app, CacheCAD allows users to selectively sync files with a simple interface. It aims to be a true GrabCAD replacement.

All user setup, permissions, and sharing settings are managed through Google's web interface, which many teams are familiar with. This eliminates concerns about data security since CacheCAD doesn't access any user data directly.

CacheCAD is free for non-commercial use and available for download, though donations are welcomed to support ongoing development. Extensive testing shows success rates over 10k file transfers in beta, though some bugs remain. Support is encouraged, and users are advised to back up files. Bug reports can be sent via DM on CD or email to mike@cachecad.com, with students instructed to include mentors in communications.

We've tested CacheCAD thoroughly, achieving over 10k successful file transfers in beta. While minor bugs exist, support is readily available. Students should include mentors in messages, and bug reports can be directed to mike@cachecad.com.

posts.name: jedgar6
posts.cooked: This may be a silly question, but I'm not very skilled with CAD—is this only for SolidWorks? I see the file types, and I don’t understand why it couldn’t be used for them, but I'm just double-checking.

posts.name: Mike Schreiber
posts.cooked: This is not exclusively for Solidworks, although the teams that have tested it now are all using Solidworks. It should work with any file types available on Google Drive, including Autodesk Inventor, Fusion 360, and PTC Creo files.

posts.name: Nick Coussens
posts.cooked: No you can use it for any local file based CAD platform. Anything you used GrabCAD for should work with CacheCAD. Mike has put a lot of work into this project and it is what is allowing our team to continue to use SolidWorks. Huge thanks to him for working on this, and I’m sure he and we are ready to help out any teams looking to utilize it.

posts.name: Brian Wagg
posts.cooked:
I spent my afternoon at work exploring Solidworks PDM and other solutions, and I can honestly say I’m experiencing significant headaches from the experience.  

Edit: Mike_Schreiber or Nick_Coussens, do you know if anyone has tested using an educational Gmail account with CacheCAD? We plan to test it ourselves too, but we'd appreciate your insights.  

You guys are doing a fantastic job! Keep it up!  

Another thing is that I have a meeting tomorrow at 3 PM related to this topic. I need to make sure I'm well-prepared for that, so I'll start studying the materials in advance.

We on 8096 have been using CacheCAD with our CAD in a Google Workspace Shared Drive owned by an edu account and accessed for the most part through edu accounts and it’s been working great. Obviously no guarantees that your school has set up the permission properly to allow it but there’s no issues inherent to educational accounts.

Edit turns out we’ve actually been using our personal accounts not school accounts. That being said Mike does agree that it should work assuming it’s not blocked by your school’s configuration.

posts.name: Nick Coussens
posts.cooked: What did Asher say earlier?

posts.name: Mike Schreiber
posts.cooked:
Schools generally block unverified apps, and Google OAuth consent limits testing to 100 users until an app is verified (which has been the obstacle preventing public release until now).  

CacheCAD successfully passed the Google verification process this week. So far, no testing issues have been encountered. Tests with email domains such as mit.edu, illinois.edu, and columbia.edu were successful. It appears feasible for most schools to allow access once their apps are verified.

posts.name: Lavi Arzi
posts.cooked: Does it support any kind of version control?

posts.name: Nick Coussens
posts.cooked: CacheCAD offers a feature to retain previous versions of CAD files either for 30 days or permanently. By default, this option is set to retain versions for 30 days, which suits most users' needs as older files rarely exceed this period. Setting it to retain versions indefinitely can consume significant storage space on Google Drive. Additionally, I regularly create occasional backups of my local CacheCAD folder to Google Drive.

posts.name: Nick Coussens
posts.cooked:
The text is:  
A CAD library being developed alongside CacheCAD offers significant advantages. This project, led by the SolidWorks team under the 8096 initiative, aims to integrate comprehensive tools and resources from major FRC vendors.

Currently, the library includes completed sections such as REV and ThriftyBot, along with a substantial collection of McMaster hardware items. Efforts are ongoing to finalize the AndyMark portion, while other segments like WCP are being managed due to upcoming updates from RC.

Key features planned for this library include:

- Magnetic mate anchor points enabling efficient drag-and-drop assembly construction.
- Mate references tailored for non-magnetic applications, such as hardware components snapping into place.
- Configurable assemblies allowing flexible selection of specific parts, including gears, pulleys, and spacers.
- Customizable part files for structural elements, enabling quick assembly without extensive customization.
- Support for COTS solutions where appropriate, such as planetary gearboxes.
- A variety of templates for rapid creation of custom parts based on standard profiles.
- Useful sketch blocks facilitating easy implementation of concepts, including motor profiles and gearbox designs.
- Optimized render quality ensuring efficient visualization in SW Photoview360.
- Accurate weight assignments, whether derived from product data or manually configured.
- Standardized naming conventions with part descriptions and vendor-specific numbers for easy organization.
- A dedicated library of 8096 parts covering diverse components like electrical mounts and modules.

For further details or suggestions, please reach out via a shared Trello or Google Sheet listing. The development timeline aims to have the library ready for public release prior to the kickoff.

posts.name: Brennan Bibic
posts.cooked: This is good stuff! Impressed with what I've been messing with for the past few hours. Using it seamlessly with our existing G Suite system so far. One issue I encountered was trying to load a project whose Google Drive folder had a slash (/) in its name, which broke the local version. A quick solution was renaming the folder, but the desktop client crashed without an obvious error message.

user_custom_fields.user_field_4: 4476 Drive Coach | SLFF The Breakfast Company

posts.name: Mike Schreiber
posts.cooked: Brennan good finds! Thanks for the feedback. I didn’t even realize you could put ‘/’ in names on Drive. I’ll have to add some checks for this and other characters that Windows doesn’t like in file or folder names. Fun fact, I recently learned Windows and Google accept emoticons in file names, but I don’t have encoding setup for them correctly so they’ll crash CacheCAD for now. Renaming a project on Drive should work, but you need to reload the project after you rename it. If you do this the local folder name and the drive name won’t match, but it will keep them linked. If you rename the local folder name it will just create a folder with the old name when you load. I suppose a better solution would be to prompt the user that the local folder and drive folder names no longer match—I’ll add that to my list.
Thank you Mike/8096 for all your work and especially for sharing it with the FIRST community. This will definitely be a useful tool.

posts.name: Andrew Torrance
posts.cooked:
Configurable assemblies of families' parts allow quick changes, iterations, etc., determining the size of a part used. Examples include single files with every ½-inch hex gear from a vendor, enabling selection of specific gears; similarly applicable to pulleys, sprockets, hex spacers, wheels, etc.

I found that making assemblies configurable instead of individual parts was confusing for students. Deleting a gear often led to inadvertently removing the internal part, causing systems to malfunction.

Additionally, integrating Magnetic mates with shaft templates that switch between journal and snap-ring shafts proved challenging due to concentricity issues affecting bearing plates, leading to system failures.

Despite these challenges, the rest of the approach seems solid and effective.

I had issues with the magnetic aligner mate, particularly when switching between journal bearings and snap-ring shafts. Adjusting the concentric alignment may resolve the problem. Disassembling the machine helped identify misalignments; tweaking settings or physical components accordingly should fix it. Testing each change ensured reliability, and iterating as needed led to effective resolution.

posts.name: Nick Coussens
posts.cooked:
If possible, have an equation-driven generation for BE file. Or if not possible, just make it configurations in a multi-body part.

I’ve found that it seems to end up loading a lot slower when it’s an equation-driven part to change teeth count for example on gears. SolidWorks now asks you if you want to delete the subassembly or the part when you select a part within an assembly and hit delete, so part of my training is to get used to hitting delete subassembly when prompted, but I agree both methods have pros and cons.

And yes, magnetic mates aren’t perfect. It does annoy me a bit that you can only have magnetic mate points on a single plane within a part, it limits the utility you can have with some parts. I’m trying to make them as useful as possible but of course parts can always be mated traditionally.

posts.name: Andrew Torrance
posts.cooked: Is it possible to set up the gear generator as a multibody instead of an assembly?

posts.name: Nick Coussens
posts.cooked: It should be possible. I can experiment to evaluate how each option performs within assemblies. I'm curious whether moving files around the assembly could cause significant lag. Additionally, I will need to decide which method to adjust which body as active based on the specific configuration.
